{{term|[[Critical point (mathematics)|Critical point]]}}
{{defn|defn=A '''critical point''' or '''stationary point''' of a [[differentiable function]] of a [[Function of a real variable|real]] or [[complex variable]] is any value in its [[domain of a function|domain]] where its [[derivative]] is 0.<ref>{{cite book | last=Stewart | first=James | authorlink=James Stewart (mathematician) | title=Calculus: Early Transcendentals |publisher=[[Brooks/Cole]] | edition=6th | year=2008 | isbn=0-495-01166-5}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last1=Larson | first1=Ron | authorlink=Ron Larson (mathematician)| last2=Edwards | first2=Bruce H. | title=Calculus | publisher=[[Brooks/Cole]] | edition=9th | year=2009 | isbn=0-547-16702-4}}</ref>}}
